\"text\":\"**Considering factory test implementation**\\n\\nI'm thinking about adding a second custom factory success test before the timeout. This would help exercise the generated class without needing a network. It involves using the `bind` and `connect` methods reflectively, but I'm not sure if it fully covers line 50. However, it doesn't seem to hurt to add it, as it might increase coverage. I believe it will be in the same file, so it could be beneficial overall.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying class naming rules**\\n\\nI’m exploring the rules around test class naming. Top-level test classes can indeed be public, and inner classes can be public static. It seems that class names don't necessarily see direct correlation to their file names. I shouldn't use `$` in test class or file names because they produce `$` in bytecode, but this doesn't apply to inner class names in source. I think I’m ready to implement these guidelines!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_5H6Q4CUfEw4KRpoZ7FUHAK1R|fc_0ccf52965e5b6820016a04623bffa88193bc73cb96bb4650da", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/commons-httpclient/commons-httpclient/3.0/src/test/java/commons_httpclient/commons_httpclient/ReflectionSocketFactoryTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "public class ReflectionSocketFactoryTest {\n    @Test\n    @Order(1)\n    void translatesReflectedSocketTimeoutException() throws Exception {", "newText": "public class ReflectionSocketFactoryTest {\n    @Test\n    @Order(1)\n    void createsSocketWithPublicFactoryClassName() throws Exception {\n        Socket socket = ReflectionSocketFactory.createSocket(RecordingSocketFactory.class.getName(), \"127.0.0.1\", 80,\n                InetAddress.getLoopbackAddress(), 0, 250);\n        if (socket == null) {\n            return;\n        }\n        try (Socket ignored = socket) {\n            assertThat(socket).isInstanceOf(RecordingSocket.class);\n            RecordingSocket recordingSocket = (RecordingSoc